The method is calling itself forever (current source):

public Vector3f getPositionWorldOnA(Vector3f positionWorldOnA) {
        getPositionWorldOnA(positionWorldOnA);
        return positionWorldOnA;
    }

Based in the code of the getPositionWorldOnB() the fix would be something like this:

public Vector3f getPositionWorldOnA(Vector3f positionWorldOnA) {
        getPositionWorldOnA(manifoldPointObjectId, positionWorldOnA);
        return positionWorldOnA;
    }

Minor issue here that makes getGravity(Vector3f gravity) return the wrong value:

Gravity parameter is setting itself (current source):

public void setGravity(Vector3f gravity) {
        gravity.set(gravity);
        setGravity(physicsSpaceId, gravity);
    }

Guess it should be something like this to set the local gravity variable:

public void setGravity(Vector3f gravity) {
        this.gravity.set(gravity);
        setGravity(physicsSpaceId, gravity);
    }

If you call setLinearDamping() and then setAngularDamping() the linear damping is not applied.

Looking at the sources they are calling different native methods:

public void setLinearDamping(float linearDamping) {
        setDamping(objectId, linearDamping, getAngularDamping());
    }

public void setAngularDamping(float angularDamping) {
        setAngularDamping(objectId, angularDamping);
    }

Calling setAngularDamping() and after setLinearDamping() or just setDamping() works ok.

I don't see a reason not to specify the return type of com.jme3.scene.control.AbstractControl#cloneForSpatial(Spatial) further, from currently Control to AbstractControl. This would in many cases relieve the user of casts. The returned object is of type AbstractControl anyway, the caller just doesn't know that.

I would suggest changing it like this:

@Override
public AbstractControl cloneForSpatial(Spatial spatial){
   //No changes to actual code.
}
